qas.question: The power to withhold royal assent has become common where?

context: During the rule of the succeeding <a0_0>Hanoverian dynasty<a0_0/>, power was gradually exercised more by parliament and the government. The first Hanoverian <b7_0>monarch<b7_0/>, <a1_0><a3_0>George I<a3_0/><a1_0/>, relied on his ministers to a greater extent than did previous monarchs. Later Hanoverian monarchs attempted to restore royal control over legislation: <b8_0>George III and George IV<b8_0/> both openly opposed <a2_0><a4_0>Catholic Emancipation<a4_0/><a2_0/> and asserted that to grant assent to a Catholic emancipation bill would violate the <a5_0>Coronation Oath<a5_0/>, which required the sovereign to preserve and protect the established Church of England from Papal domination and would grant rights to individuals who were in league with a foreign power which did not recognise their legitimacy. However, <a6_0>George IV<a6_0/> reluctantly granted his assent upon the advice of his <b9_0>ministers<b9_0/>. Thus, as the concept of ministerial responsibility has evolved, the power to withhold royal assent has fallen into disuse, both <b10_0>in the United Kingdom and in the other Commonwealth realms<b10_0/>.
